-- Crude Options Decline After Futures Advance Fourth-Straight Day
-- B y   D a n   M u r t a u g h
-- 2013-08-14T21:30:38Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-08-14/crude-options-decline-after-futures-advance-fourth-straight-day.html
Crude oil options volatility
declined as the underlying futures advanced for the fourth day
in a row.  Implied volatility for at-the-money options expiring in
October was 21.69 percent on the  New York Mercantile Exchange  at
5 p.m., down from 21.81 yesterday.  Volatility for calls protecting against a 10 percent
increase in prices rose to 22.8 percent from 22.41 percent
yesterday. Volatility for puts covering a 10 percent price drop
advanced to 24.78 percent from 24.54 percent.  Volatility levels for November and December options rose
and were above October volatility.  West Texas Intermediate crude for October delivery gained
16 cents to settle at $106.56 a barrel on the Nymex. Itâ€™s the
third day in a row with a gain of less than $1 a barrel.
September-delivery futures rose 2 cents to $106.85.  The most active options in electronic trading today were
September $106 puts, which lost 31 cents to 17 cents a barrel on
volume of 4,387 lots as of 5:07 p.m. September $105 puts were
the second-most active, dropping 18 cents to 5 cents a barrel on
volume of 4,322 contracts.  September options expire tomorrow.  Bearish bets made up 57 percent of electronic trading
volume. In the prior session, calls accounted for 52 percent of
the 120,600 contracts exchanged.  September $105 puts were the most-active options yesterday,
with 5,083 lots exchanging hands as they slid 33 cents to 23
cents a barrel. October $130 calls were next, unchanged at 4
cents a barrel on volume of 4,812 contracts.  Open interest was highest for December $80 puts, with
39,630 contracts. Next were December $90 puts with 37,067 lots
and December $100 calls with 35,247.  The exchange distributes real-time data for electronic
trading and releases information the next business day on open-outcry volume, where the bulk of options activity occurs.  To contact the reporter on this story:
